{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "New research shows how we can be fooled by our instinctive belief in patterns.", "abstract": "News Analysis; number of studies have shown degree to which people, including scientists, are fooled by cognitive biases, particularly those influenced by human inclination to find patterns even in seemingly random events; flaws in perception of randomness can affect everything from gambling to scientific research, and can shed light on so-called replication crisis in science, where results of tests cannot be replicated.", "section_name": "Sunday Review", "print_page": "4", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "George", "role": "reported", "lastname": "JOHNSON", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By GEORGE JOHNSON"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/18/sunday-review/gamblers-scientists-and-the-mysterious-hot-hand.html", "lead_paragraph": "New research shows how we can be fooled by our instinctive belief in patterns.", "headline": {"print_headline": "Gamblers, Scientists and the Hot Hand", "main": "Gamblers, Scientists and the Mysterious Hot Hand", "content_kicker": "News Analysis", "kicker": "News Analysis"}, "_id": "562293b138f0d815e8e112f9", "word_count": "1410", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/10/18/opinion/sunday/18johnson/18johnson-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/10/18/opinion/sunday/18johnson/18johnson-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 371, "url": "images/2015/10/18/opinion/sunday/18johnson/18johnson-articleLarge.gif", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/10/18/opinion/sunday/18johnson/18johnson-articleLarge.gif", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "371"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/10/18/opinion/sunday/18johnson/18johnson-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2015/10/18/opinion/sunday/18j